data.title: My life as an NPC- Part 1

images.description:
I'm a baker. I work in a very unique situation- my kitchen is very public so a lot of people know me but I do not know the people. I am part of a ton of people's daily commute since 2 major transit lines pass my work, and a lot of people walk.

I would like to offer some insight on what I do most days.
I work at 4 am. Luckily I work about 4 minutes from my house so I can sleep in a little bit. It takes me about 30 minutes to shower, dress, braid my hair and drink 2 coffees.
I drink more coffee when I get to work. I probably drink about 8 coffees a day. I also drink about 4 litres of water.

data.title: Thank you?
data.description:
tl;dr: I bring in tasty goodies to share, but apparently no one knows it's me bringing them in. 

So, I started my new job a few months back and every week or so, I bring in sandwiches, wraps, cookies, cupcakes, donuts, soda, and/or candy and put it all out on the break room table with a note that says, "Help yourself!" 

Everyone seems to enjoy everything and stuff's usually gone in short order, which makes me happy because some days, you really need that break room hero. 

Well, I brought in cupcakes, cookies, spoopy lollipops, a couple of bottles of soda, and little individually wrapped glow-in-the-dark fangs that come with little 'blood bag' candies. Get everyone in the Halloween spirit and all that! 

It was the end of my shift and I decided to relax in the break room for 15 and have a cookie before leaving. I'd just finished it and was browsing imgur when my manager came in. "You can eat those things, you know," she says, helpfully, "They're for everyone, even you." 

It only struck me then that no one knew who was bringing food in and I realised I'd never actually TOLD anyone that the food was back there except some cryptic note on a piece of paper towel or something. I didn't really want to say anything, because it was kind of awkward being given permission to eat the food I bought so I said, "Oh! Cool! Thanks!" before watching her leave again. 

The way I see it, I don't really need the credit if no one knows because it's really just about cheering everyone up during a dull work week. At the same time, it was just so awkward.

data.title: A different kind of birthday celebration.

images.description:
So this morning I went to the grocery store to pick up my sons birthday cake. The woman at the bakery said "I have a story to tell you about the cake." I'm thinking oh boy something must have happened with the cake. Well a woman had come to the bakery and asked if any children's bday cakes were being picked up today. Today was her son's bday but he had passed away and she wanted to pay for a child's cake in remembrance of him. The woman working in the bakery said "your cake has been paid for and this person left you a card." Needless to say there were lots of tears as I walked away with our cake. Thank you to this amazing Mom! My heart goes out to you. We appreciated our celebration a little extra today and I am vowing to pay this kindness forward.

Credit: My friend Kelly K.

data.title: Bladesmithing - Getting Started
data.description: Showing my first year of becoming a bladesmith

images.description:
After watching several seasons of Forged In Fire, I thought bladesmithing looked like a fun hobby, though wasn't sure how to get started.  One item I knew I needed was an anvil, but didn't want to spend the $500 for an entry level forging anvil.  Especially on a new hobby that I may find I don't actually like.

Lucky for me, I came up on my 5 year work anniversary at OST, and was offered a very nice watch as a present.  I asked, and was granted, to select something of equal or lesser value for my gift.  My new 77lbs Kanca anvil arrive via UPS about a week later!

https://www.centaurforge.com/Kanca-77-lbs-Drop-Forged-Double-Horn-Anvil-35-KG/productinfo/DFA77DH/
Freshly unpacked anvil.  Aside from a few other common tools, this is how it started.
Living in the city, I don't have many options for workspaces.  I resigned myself to parking in the driveway, and began building a workbench.

Unbroken Soviet POW stares down Heinrich Himmler

images.description:
ReichsfÃ¼hrer-SS Heinrich Himmler visits a POW camp in Minsk, USSR in August 1941. German policy towards Soviet POW was horrid: these people were treated worse than animals. It is estimated that about 3.5 million Soviet POWs died due to deliberate starvation, torture and murder by their German captors. They were kept in appalling, inhumane living conditions. Given no housing in their camps, prisoners had to dig holes in order to seek shelter and mostly defecated and urinated in a very cramped and over-filled area. Typhoid fever was rampant, and due to deliberate starvation, prisoners would often resort to cannibalism. Conditions in the POW camps for Soviet prisoners were often much worse than in the concentration camps.

Due to the immense numbers of prisoners taken during Operation Barbarossa in 1941 and the mobile nature of that operation, prisoners were force-marched and given little sustenance, mostly surviving on a couple of hundred calories a day. They were often subject to the humiliation by SS guards, with some loaves of bread thrown into the masses of prisoners, many of them killing each other for the rare chance to eat. In some cruel cases of sadistic amusement, prisoners were tied together on fences and grenades were thrown at them, either being killed or losing their limbs. It was a sadistic and cruel â€œconfirmationâ€ for the Nazi fanatics that the Soviets were subhumans and lived and behaved like animals.

In the cold Russian winters, Soviet POWs were given no clothing and little rations. Limbs would become gangrenous (black due to tissue-death) and many would die of typhoid fever, starvation, hypothermia and sheer exhaustion. 

The horror of the Eastern Front remains incomprehensible to those who have never experienced it. It was the single, most brutal military campaign in history. A war of extermination.

Should be a Wonder of the World but isn't: Kailasa Temple

images.description:
Wanted to share what I think is one of the most incredible human achievements that other people should know about, Kailasa Temple.

This temple, in Maharashtra, India, is the largest stone cut temple in the world. Meaning the entire thing was cut into the mountainside from one rock. I repeat, from ONE ROCK. In the 8th century, using hammers and chisels.

If you zoom in you can see visitors, giving you an idea of scale.

It was apparently made in the shape of a chariot in dedication to Shiva. You can read more on wikipedia here: https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kailasa_temple,_Ellora
If others have resources about this place, please link them. I just want to share photos and raise awareness of how incredible this is.

data.title: A look at Spellbreakâ€™s Conduit class!

images.description:
Hey imgur! Weâ€™re back with more behind-the-scenes looks at Spellbreakâ€™s pre-alpha development. This gallery is the second in our series on the gameâ€™s Class system and is focused on the lightning school of magic: Conduit.

Class basics: Early in development, we decided to incorporate RPG elements, which led us to develop a system of â€œclassesâ€ that add depth to how players build out their characters. In each match, you are given the opportunity to select and develop two classes. Each class contains a passive ability and three scrolls that you choose and level up over the course of a match.

(if youâ€™re new to this project, we're working on a multiplayer PvP game with spellcasting combat and RPG elements. We've been posting updates here over the past few months https://proletariatgames.imgur.com while the game has been in pre-alpha testing, and hope to keep doing so throughout development.)

===

Conduit's Passive Ability: Lightning Fast - Increases sprint speed by 20%, but breaks briefly when you attack or take damage. Most of the gifs in the gallery demonstrate it, so I wonâ€™t post an extraâ€¦running gif :)

This is a good ability to start a match with. No one will ever say itâ€™s overpowered, but being able to move faster than normal without having to use an equipment slot AND have it active through the whole match is very useful. Conduit is a great choice right off the bat if youâ€™re starting in a far-off location or want to do a bunch of looting.

Scroll: Arc Flash - Your lightning bolts have a 25/50/75% chance to leave behind a ball of lightning that strikes nearby players.

An important design consideration is to let players feel powerful even if theyâ€™re not incredibly mechanically skillful (not all the time, mind you; just a consideration). You see this in the various spells, but also in places like Arc Flash. If you hit someone with lighting, itâ€™s very damaging, but itâ€™s also a relatively small projectile with some spread on subsequent shots so itâ€™s not super easy to hit targets. Arc Flash gives those missed shots a chance to do some work on their own.

Strategically, you can use it to lay down a killing field just by littering the ground with ball lightnings if you have a few moments before a fight or if you see someone teleporting your way. You can also use them as sentries that will notify you if someone is coming from behind you or from around a corner or use them to cover your escape.

Scroll: Charged Rune - After using your rune, fire arcs of lightning towards the nearest 2/3/4 people for 30/45/60 damage (has 3 second cooldown).

In Spellbreak, you generally have five active buttons, your two spells, your two sorceries, and your rune. We wondered what would happen if you could trigger other abilities but without the overhead of additional active abilities. Enter Charged Rune! At its base, it functions as a burst damage option if youâ€™re planning ahead or ambient/incidental damage if youâ€™re not, but you can also do fancier things like use it to do damage while jumping over one target while shooting someone else in the distance or use it to pop an invisible person sneaking up on you who thinks theyâ€™re safe. It raises the skill cap a little but without adding complexity to the control scheme.

Development fun fact!: Originally this didnâ€™t have a cooldown and players could load up on rune charges, waddle up next to someone and vaporize them by blowing all their charges at once. It wasâ€¦not ideal but it was funny to see someone stealth into a group and then detonate everyone at once.
Worth it with sound!

data.title: The true story of David Hahn, the Radioactive Boy Scout

images.description: This is David. David as a teenage boy, built a fully functioning Nuclear Reactor in his back yard with homemade materials. He did this partially because he was interested in becoming an eagle scout, but the real reason is that this teenager is simply a Mad Lad. This shitpost is his true story. As told in both the Harpers Magazine Article in Nov 1998 (PDF link at the end) and other sources for his life after 1998, and links to two books written about him.

David was always an obsessive goofy kid, that enjoyed projects. Even at the young age of six he was known for conducting experiments, and had a deep love and passion for chemistry. It was also at this his parents divorced. Which only made him enjoy his experiments a little more.

He lived with his mother and her boyfriend on the weekends and a young kid in a new area with no friends is kind of lonely. So at the age of 10, his grandfather gave him this book, The Golden Book of Chemistry experiments, to help keep him occupied on the weekend, and fuel his love of science. He converted the basement of his mom's house to a lab. And when he was older he would deliever newspapers, work at fast food joints and do other odd jobs to get components and supplies for his hobby.

data.title: I made a set nightstands out of thin slices of wood together
data.description: I built a set of new night stands for myself using strips of ash and walnut cut to random lengths and all glued together.

images.description:
Here it is! What a project this was. Probably took me closeÂ to a month to finish as I was only working on it in my spare time on weekends and after work on occasion. Definitely one of my longest projects, but totally worth it! I'm really happy with how it all turned out!

If you haven't seen one of my builds before (you probably haven't, the internet is a big place after all) and you like what you see. Check me out on Instagram at https://www.instagram.com/zacharyms/ I post all my stuff there as well as random DIY tips, tricks and etc. 

Years ago I saw a coffee table that had a mosaic wood pattern that slowly transitioned from a darker wood to a lighter wood and it' been stuck in my mind ever since. Recently I was trying to brainstorm some designs for a nightstand for my bedroom and figured I'd finally do my own take on it. These are the results!

I liked it so much that I made 2 of them! Everyone knows you ain't shit if you don't have a matching set of nightstands (obviously just kidding, this is my first matching set). 

As you can see each nightstand is approximately 50% ash and 50% walnut, I wanted each nightstand to "fade" from the darker wood (walnut) to the lighter wood (ash).

Here they are set up in my bedroom! Ok, you're right, the other shots were in my bedroom too, but on the other side of the room. Nothing gets by you. 

My bedframe is made of walnut, so obviously, the walnut side of each nightstand faces towards the bedframe. As you move away from the bed frame the nightstands transition to ash. 

In the future, I'd like to build on this concept and add some ash shelves in the corners on either side of my bed. A couple of triangular shelves in each corner will look good.
You name it, weâ€™ll bitch about it.                 FPedit: send your baby animals and spread some cuteness in the world.

data.title: When you feel you can't go on.
data.description:
A very dear friend of mine shared this with me during a time I was at my lowest.  Different messages help different people in different ways. This one helped me. I hope it can help someone else.

https://youtu.be/urZxLdrwcbQRaymond Reddington - The Blacklist. ( best to listen to him)

"Have you ever seen the aftermath of a suicide bombingâ€¦
I have. June 29, 2003. I was meeting two associates at the Marouche restaurant in Tel Aviv. As my car was pulling up, a 20-year-old Palestinian named Ghazi Safar entered the restaurant and detonated a vest wired with C4.
The shock wave knocked me flat, blew out my eardrums. I couldnâ€™t hear. The smokeâ€¦ It was like being underwater. I went inside. A nightmare. Blood. Parts of people. You could tell where Safar was standing when the vest blew. It was like a perfect circle of death. There was almost nothing left of the people closest to him. 17 dead, 46 injured. Blown to pieces. The closer they were to the bomber, the more horrific the effect.
Thatâ€™s every suicide. Every single one. An act of terror perpetrated against everyone whoâ€™s ever known youâ€¦ Everyone whoâ€™s ever loved you. The people closest to youâ€¦ the ones who cherish youâ€¦ are the ones who suffer the most pain, the most damage. Why would you do that?"
